.TH _PRINTF 3 "MARCH 2026" "ALX Software Engineering" "Custom Printf Manual"
.SH NAME
_printf \- formatted output conversion
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.br
.BI "int _printf(const char *" format ", ...);"
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \fB_printf\fP() function produces output according to a \fIformat\fP as described below. It writes output to stdout, the standard output stream.
.PP
The format string is composed of zero or more directives: ordinary characters (not %), which are copied unchanged to the output stream; and conversion specifications, each of which results in fetching zero or more subsequent arguments. 
.br
Please note that any character following % which does not match a supported conversion specifier will be printed as is.
.SH RETURN VALUE
Upon success, \fB_printf\fP() returns the number of characters printed (excluding the null byte used to end output to strings). If an output error is encountered, a value of -1 is returned.
.SH CONVERSION SPECIFIERS
.TP
.B %%
A '%' is written. No argument is converted.
.TP
.B %c
The \fBint\fP argument is converted to an \fBunsigned char\fP, and the resulting character is written.
.TP
.B %s
The \fBconst char *\fP argument is expected to be a pointer to an array of character type (pointer to a string). Characters from the array are written up to (but not including) the terminating null byte.
.TP
.B %d, %i
The \fBint\fP argument is converted to signed decimal notation.
.TP
.B %u
The \fBunsigned int\fP argument is printed as is in decimal notation.
TP
.TP
.B %o
The \fBunsigned int\fP argument is printed with on the fly conversion for octal representation.
.TP
.B %x
The \fBunsigned int\fP argument is printed with on the fly conversion for lowercase hexadecimal representation.
.TP
.B %X
The \fBunsigned int\fP argument is printed with on the fly conversion for UPPERcase hexadecimal representation.
.SH EXAMPLES
.B _printf("Character: [%c]\\n", 'H');
.br
.B _printf("String: [%s]\\n", "I am a string!");
.br
.B _printf("Integer: [%i]\\n", 136427834);
.br
.B _printf("Negative: [%d]\\n", -762534);
.br
.B _printf("Unsigned (777777): [%o]\\n", 777777);
.br
.B _printf("Octal (777 -> 1411): [%o]\\n", 777);
.br
.B _printf("Lowercase Hexa (7777 -> 1e61): [%x]\\n", 7777);
.br
.B _printf("Uppercase Hexa (7777 -> 1E61): [%X]\\n", 7777);
.br
.SH SEE ALSO
printf(3), write(2)
